<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Woerner: NATO Air Strikes Still Possible in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701121294 Paris AFP in English 1206 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0701121294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Jan 7 (AFP) -- The West is still holding 
open the option of air strikes to free up relief shipments in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner said 
here Friday [7 January]. 
  The North Atlantic Treaty Organisation agreed in August to 
launch air attacks on Bosnian Serbs if requested by the United 
Nations to break the siege of Sarajevo and other mainly Moslem 
communities. 
  "The concept to which we agreed in August is still valid," 
Woerner told reporters three days before a NATO summit where 
France plans to make a new push for action on Bosnia amid 
increased shelling of Sarajevo. 
  "I have no doubt that if we would be confronted with a 
request by UNPROFOR (the United Nations Protection Force) or the 
secretary general of the United Nations, NATO would be prepared 
to do what it promised to do," he said. 
  Woerner also predicted the 16-member alliance would be ready 
to help implement any peace accord reached to end the 
21-month-old conflict in the former Yugoslav republic. 
  NATO has drafted plans to send a 50,000-strong force, half 
of 
it from the United States. But doubts have been raised whether 
Washington would contribute its share after its peacekeeping 
problems in Somalia and Haiti. 
  "I think if really the chips are down and the implementation 
of a possible peace plan depends on NATO support, I think there 
is a good chance that the United States will participate," 
Woerner said. "But that is my own guess." 
  Despite pressure by France, he did not think the Bosnian 
conflict would dominate the summit, which will take up such 
issues as ties to the former eastern bloc and strengthening 
NATO's European pillar. 
  "This summit has as the major objective to prepare this 
alliance for the future, to set it on track even for the 21st 
century," Woerner said. 

</TEXT>

