<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demirel Addresses Foreign Envoys </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0601191494 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1445 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0601191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Dec. 6 (AA) -- President Suleyman Demirel 
said today that 1994 will hopefully be a year when aggressors 
will eventually have some common sense. 
  He was addressing the heads of foreign missions in Ankara, 
for whom he hosted a reception on the occasion of the new year. 
  Demirel recalled that after the decease of President Turgut 
Ozal in 1993 he was elected president and meanwhile, leaders of 
leading political parties have also been replaced. [sentence as 
received] 
  Before being elected president, Suleyman Demirel was premier 
and leader of the major coalition partner True Path Party. 
  "All this process took place without hindering the normal 
functioning of the government and the daily lives of citizens, 
within the Constitution and current legislation," he said. 
  Demirel went on to say that Turkey faced great problems in 
the field of foreign policy in 1993. 
  "Instability in the Caucasus and the Balkans and terrorist 
activities aimed from other regions to Turkey, were the main 
issues troubling us. 
  "However, the Turkish governments which were not influenced 
by provocations chose to seek solutions by calling the 
international community to enter multifaceted cooperation. 
  "Turkey has at all times displayed an attitude of compromise 
and moderation," Demirel said. 
  "We hope that 1994 becomes a year which the aggressors 
eventually come to common sense, Armenians withdraw from the 
Azeri land they invaded, the disputes in Georgia are resolved 
and the embargo which creates great grievances for the Iraqi 
people ends and efforts to bring peace to the Middle East 
finally yield a solution," he added. 
  "I am aware that the year 1993 had been a very busy one for 
you diplomats who endeavoured to follow developments in and 
around Turkey. I assure you that the year 1994 will not be 
dissapointing for you," he concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

