<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows CDA Losing Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0701100394 Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD in Dutch 6 Jan 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> BR0701100394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Christian Democratic Appeal Losing </F>
Popularity Among Voters"] 
  [Text] The Hague -- The CDA [Christian Democratic Appeal] 
is becoming increasingly unsuccessful in the battle for the 
voters' favor, opinion polls show. The most recent poll by the 
InterView research bureau shows that the Christian Democrats' 
attractiveness under Mr. Brinkman is declining. 
  If parliamentary elections were to be held now, the CDA 
would 
obtain only 38 seats, a loss of 16. Various polls since 
mid-December have suddenly pointed to a significant loss for the 
largest government party. 
  The poll results, which were announced on television 
yesterday evening, also show that the PvdA [Labor Party] is 
still facing heavy losses: 27 seats, compared with 49 in the 
1989 elections. The VVD [People's Party for Freedom and 
Democracy] and D66 [Democrats 66] opposition parties would both 
win 7 and 20 seats respectively, taking them to 29 and 32 places 
in Parliament. 
  The last day of the poll was the day before Christmas. In 
addition, one-third of those asked said that they did not yet 
know which party they would vote for on 3 May. 

</TEXT>

