<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatian Envoy Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701112694 Cologne Deutschlandfunk Network in German 0615 
GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0701112694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cologne Deutschlandfunk Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Croatian Ambassador to Germany </F>
Professor Ivan Ilic by unidentified announcer -- live] 
  [Excerpts] [Announcer] Ambassador, why was Bonn chosen as 
the venue for the talks between Franjo Tudjman and Alija 
Izetbegovic? 
  [Ilic] Why Bonn? One could say that President Tudjman made 
the suggestion to continue the talks in Bonn, after Vienna. 
President Izetbegovic agreed and both sides asked the German 
side to host the talks. Germany has so far made great efforts 
to bring about peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina. It has the complete 
trust of both sides. 
  [Announcer] So this initiative to choose Bonn as the venue 
for the meeting was made by Croatia and not by the German 
Government? 
  [Ilic] That is correct. [words indistinct] the initiative 
came from the Croatian side and, one could say, also from the 
Bosnian side. 
  [Announcer] Ambassador, could the German Government mediate 
a 
little during the meeting, even though the Foreign Ministry 
officially denies this? 
  [Ilic] As far as I can see, the Federal Republic of Germany 
will in this case not directly participate in the talks; it will 
only be the host. [passage omitted] 
  [Announcer] We now have the Owen-Stoltenberg plan, which 
envisages a three-way split of Bosnia-Herzegovina into a Muslim, 
Croat, and Serb part. It is obvious that before such a plan is 
signed all sides will attempt to secure as much territory as 
possible. Should such a three-way split come about, will 
Croatia aim to unite with the Croatian territories in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina in the future? 
  [Ilic] Croatia wants, and it is in the interest of Croatia, 
that Bosnia-Herzegovina remains a whole, a whole state. Croatia 
does not want to annex anything. Croatia only wants to defend 
the Croat people in Bosnia-Herzegovina. It is obvious though 
that the Serbs want to create a greater Serbia and that is where 
the idea of a breakup of Bosnia-Herzegovina emerges. The 
Croatian side does not want this. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

