<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruehe Favors NATO Membership for East Europe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701093894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0125 GMT 7 Jan 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD0701093894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Hanover/Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- In contrast to 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, Defense Minister Volker Ruehe favors the 
early accession of Poland, Hungary, and other reform states to 
NATO. There are also leading deputies within the CDU/CSU 
[Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union] 
parliamentary group who do not agree with Kohl's rejectionist 
stance, the HANNOVERSCHE ALLGEMEINE ZEITUNG (Friday [7 January] 
edition) reports. 
  Within CDU/CSU circles in Bonn it was being said on Thursday 
that Ruehe is very disappointed that the Chancellor has 
"apparently changed" his stance following his talks with Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin shortly before Christmas. This came as 
a shock to the Defense Ministry, the newspaper writes. Hence 
Ruehe is "quite relieved" not to have to attend the NATO summit 
next week. 
  Ruehe, it is being said within his entourage, is "very 
unhappy" that Kohl and Foreign Minister Kinkel attach great 
weight to U.S. concerns about broadening membership to the East. 
If Kohl takes the same view on the issue as he does, he should 
not relinquish that view because of diplomatic considerations, 
Ruehe says. 
  The report goes on to say that it is not enough to say 
simply 
that one does "not totally rule out" NATO membership for those 
states. Attempts must be made to bring about their entry. 
Support must be given in the political, economic, and military 
spheres. The Defense Ministry sees reform of the armed forces 
as a criterion for membership. Structures must be comparable 
and the military leadership must embrace the same values. There 
are reservations within the Defense Ministry on isolated 
membership for the Baltic states because here the risks are in 
reality greater than the benefits. [Passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

