<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paris Requests U.S. Military Assistance in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0701114894 Paris LE MONDE in French 7 Jan 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> BR0701114894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE MONDE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "According to Mr. Leotard's </F>
Entourage, France Requested Military Assistance From Washington"] 
  [Text] A source close to Mr. Leotard revealed on Wednesday, 
5 January, that France has called on the United States to 
provide assistance for two military operations in Bosnia aimed 
at relieving the Muslim enclaves besieged by Serbs. The same 
source stated that Paris expects Washington to provide military 
air support and logistics assistance to reopen the Tuzla 
airfield in northern Bosnia and to make it possible for a Danish 
UNPROFOR [United Nations Protection Forces] armored column to 
relieve a Canadian unit in Srebrenica in the east. 
  Questioned on those statements, diplomats from the Quai 
d'Orsay [Foreign Ministry] could not explain what France exactly 
sought from the United States. They said that Paris would urge 
the United States, at next week's NATO summit, to respect the 
commitments it made. 
  According to them, this refers to the military air support 
that NATO pledged to provide the blue helmets with last August 
if they needed it. But the diplomats stated that the UNPROFOR 
has never requested any such assistance, except for 
reconnaissance missions. 
<H5>  Mr. Mitterrand: "Unacceptable" </H5>
  Meanwhile, while receiving the New Year wishes of the 
diplomatic corps, President Mitterrand warned against the 
possibility of an "even more dramatic situation" in former 
Yugoslavia. He outlined the dilemma that faces the countries 
involved in the UNPROFOR. "Should we continue to let people kill 
each other to the last man? Should we stay and be the target 
that takes the blows of those who like death, as was said during 
the Spanish [Civil] War?" he asked. "In both cases, the 
situation is unacceptable. We thus must ensure that the 
development (...) of this deadlocked situation does not give 
rise to an even more dramatic situation." 

</TEXT>

