<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-005 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Said To Continue To Arm Indonesia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601192794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1733 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Schwerin (DDP/ADN) -- According to information in 
the SCHWERINER VOLKSZEITUNG newspaper, the Federal Government 
will continue to arm the Indonesian Navy. Parallel to the 
decision to deliver 39 former warships from the NVA [National 
People's Army of the former GDR] to the highly indebted 
island-state, the Federal Security Council has also approved the 
export of a 209 class submarine. Bonn has also given the green 
light for the options for the construction of two further 
submarines. The article is based on Bonn's response to a 
question from SPD [Social Democratic Party] Bundestag deputies 
on arms deals with Indonesia, the paper writes (Friday [7 
January] edition). 
  The submarines, each of which costs 665.1 million German 
marks [DM], are covered by the Hermes government export credit 
guarantee. At the same time, the Federal Government has 
admitted that, contrary to previous statements, it has only 
partially demilitarized the former NVA ships or has supplied 
them as complete weapons systems to the Indonesian Navy, it is 
further reported. Sixteen "Parchim" ships have thus been handed 
over to the Indonesian Navy in a fully equipped state. The 
delivery of the 39 NVA ships has also been guaranteed to the 
tune of DM689.9 million. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-58125 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu005_i_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-005 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mitterrand: Force `Could Deepen' Bosnian Conflict </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0601215194 Paris AFP in English 2142 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0601215194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 6 (AFP) -- The UN should resist mounting 
pressure to pull its forces out of war-torn Bosnia-Hercegovina, 
French President Francois Mitterrand said Thursday [6 January], 
but he warned the use of force by UN troops in the ex-Yugoslavia 
could deepen the Balkans conflict. 
  But in his traditional New Year's press conference, 
Mitterrand said: "I would not wish to see a withdrawal of the UN 
troops because that would amount to abandoning the civilians 
even more than they are already. 
  "To say to these people, tear yourselves to pieces (...) I 
could not imagine such a thing," said the French leader, who 
paid tribute to UN forces in former Yugoslav state who had 
"sometimes paid with their lives." [passage omitted] 
  Mitterrand backed the use of force to carry out the UN 
mission in Bosnia but said doing so risked "spreading the 
infection of war, little by little," adding that "our policy 
must be sufficiently courageous but also very prudent. 
  "1994 will not go by without some important innovations" in 
policy on Bosnia, he said. 
  The president expressed measured support for a call by 
French 
Defence Minister Francois Leotard for US involvement in the 
conflict, saying "if there was the need for air cover for UN 
soldiers, why not?" 
  In a wide-ranging press conference the French leader 
expressed concern for the rise in Islamic fundamentalism in 
Algeria, a former French colony, saying "we have the right to be 
worried about fundamentalist campaigns." 
  And in a passing reference to his health the 76-year-old 
president, who suffers from prostate cancer, said there was 
"nothing to report." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-58126 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu006__a94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-006-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kohl Wants `Clear' NATO Prospects for East Europe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801132394 Hamburg DPA in German Hamburg DPA in German 
1224 GMT 8 Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0801132394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>Language: &lt;f 105&gt; German 
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Hamburg (DPA) -- On the eve of the 10 January 
NATO summit in Brussels, Chancellor Helmut Kohl has called for 
the East European states to be given clear prospects of 
membership. The justified security needs of Germany's eastern 
neighbors, like Poland and the Czech Republic, needed to be 
taken "very seriously," the Chancellor told FRANKFURTER 
ALLGEMEINE ZEITUNG. He was also in favor of these countries 
joining the European Union (EU) when they fulfill the economic 
preconditions for doing so. 
  Kohl once again came out in favor of further expanding 
security links between NATO and Russia. Without mentioning the 
name of Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, leader of the extreme right-wing 
Liberal Democratic Party of Russia, Kohl said the recent "shrill 
extremist noises" from Moscow should not dissuade NATO from 
continuing on this path. On the contrary, they were an 
additional reason to maintain the close relations with 
particular care. He supported the reform politics of Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin and expected that in the process of 
building a democratic order, "relapses into old thinking" could 
be warded off. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

