<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kohl Supports NATO Partnership for Peace Offer </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001134394 Hamburg DPA in German 1255 GMT 10 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1001134394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels (DPA) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has 
pressed for closer political and military cooperation between 
NATO and the reform states of Central and Eastern Europe. Kohl 
told the heads of state and government during the opening of the 
alliance's two-day conference in Brussels today that the 
alliance had to take seriously the "understandable security 
policy concerns" of the states of Central, Eastern, and 
southeastern Europe. The people in these countries currently 
felt they were living in a "gray zone of security." 
  For this reason, NATO's offer of "Partnership for Peace" 
also 
opened up the prospect of joining the Atlantic alliance. Kohl 
stressed, however, that "nobody is able to give a concrete date 
for this at the moment." Training for participation in 
international peace missions could number among the joint 
activities envisaged. 
  Kohl is also prepared to offer the reform states immediate 
consultations if they are faced with a threat. This made clear 
that the offer of a Partnership for Peace was not merely a 
diplomatic cliche, "but a seriously intended step on the path 
toward later membership," Kohl said. 
  No new rifts should be created in Europe. A relationship 
based on partnership had to be developed with Russia and 
Ukraine. Policies of partnership, responsibility, and 
constructive involvement in international problems were expected 
from the Russian side. Attempts at hegemony could not be 
reconciled with these expectations, Kohl said. 

</TEXT>

