<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPD Leader Warns NATO Not To Expand `Too Quickly' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001114594 Hamburg DPA in German 0355 GMT 10 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1001114594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg (DPA)--In the run-up to the NATO summit in 
Brussels, SPD Chairman Rudolf Scharping has warned against 
accepting the eastern European countries into the western 
alliance too quickly. Scharping told the BILD newspaper (Monday 
[10 January] edition): "The legitimate security interests of 
Russia and the other CIS states have to be considered in this. 
We must not give the nationalist, partly fascist, in any case 
antiwestern and anti democratic forces in Russia any cheap 
excuses. So this has to be a process of several stages that 
must not ignore the economic side of things, in particular." 
  The SPD leader also stressed that the Central and East 
European states' fear of "being under Moscow's control again" 
had to be taken seriously. It was therefore "sensible to use 
existing instruments -- NATO and CSCE -- to give states such as 
Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, possibly also Slovakia and 
others, security prospects." The SPD chairman stressed, 
however, that Russian membership of NATO was "unrealistic from 
today's point of view." (This report was prereleased to DPA in 
an edited form) 

</TEXT>

