<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Kozyrev Discusses NATO Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701174894 Hamburg DPA in German 1630 GMT 7 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0701174894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Frankfurt (DPA) -- To prevent Europe from splitting 
once again, Russia has proposed a new "strategy of partnership" 
to the West and other European states. In a signed article for 
the FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU (Saturday's [8 January] edition), 
Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev warns against 
"fragmentation tendencies" in Europe. 
  If NATO expands towards the east "over-hastily," a dangerous 
situation will arise in Europe -- like the one that arose from 
the Treaty of Versailles after World War I. Kozyrev said that 
admitting Poland or other Central and East European states to 
NATO would mean shifting the "guardhouse on the Rhine" to the 
"banks of the Bug." 
  The core of the Russian proposal was the idea of taking all 
steps towards a "new European architecture" on a joint, equal 
basis. Regional organizations such as the EU [European Union], 
NATO, or the WEU [Western European Union] had to be open to all 
democratic countries. Even Russia did not rule out a priori 
that it could apply for admission to NATO at some stage in the 
future, Kozyrev announced. 
  Kozyrev says that the "guarantee of the same security level 
for all European states" and the "exclusion of territorial 
claims" were among the principles of the partnership strategy 
proposed by him. The Russian Government's specific proposal was 
that the North Atlantic Cooperation Council, in which all NATO 
and former Warsaw Pact countries are represented, should be made 
into a central organization for military cooperation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

