<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   British General To Replace Briquemont </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0701091994 London HERMES Database in English 5 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0701091994 </F>
<F P=104>  London HERMES Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Press release issued by the UK Defense Ministry on 5 </F>
January: "UN Appointment for British General in Bosnia"] 
  [Text] The United Nations announced today that Lieutenant 
General Sir Michael Rose will assume command of the UN 
Protection Force [UNPROFOR] Bosnia-Herzegovina. He will succeed 
the current Belgian Commander, Lieutenant General Francis 
Briquemont. 
  Lieutenant General Rose will have his headquarters in 
Kiseljak in Central Bosnia. He will be responsible to the 
overall Commander of UNPROFOR in the Former Yugoslavia, General 
Jean Cot, who has his headquarters in Zagreb, Croatia. 
<H5>  Biographical Details </H5>
  Lieutenant General Sir Michael Rose was born in Quetta in 
1940 and educated at Cheltenham, Oxford and the Sorbonne. He was 
commissioned into the Coldstream Guards in 1964, and served in 
Aden, Germany and Northern Ireland. Following attendance at the 
Staff College, Camberley in 1973, he was appointed Brigade Major 
of 16 Parachute Brigade and subsequently commanded a squadron of 
22 Special Air Service Regiment. 
  Following a tour of duty in Northern Ireland as Military 
Assistant to the General Officer Commanding, he returned to 
command 22d Special Air Service Regiment from 1979-1982, during 
which time he saw active service in the Falkland Islands. From 
there he went on to command 39th Infantry Brigade in Northern 
Ireland. 
  He attended the Royal College of Defence Studies in 1986, 
and 
from January 1987 until May 1988 was Commandant of the School of 
Infantry. He was Director Special Forces until his appointment 
as General Officer Commanding North East District and 2d 
Infantry Division in October 1989. He then took over as 
Commandant of the Staff College, Camberley. This was his last 
appointment before becoming Commander UK Field Army and 
Inspector General Territorial Army in April 1993. He was awarded 
the QGM [Queen's Gallantry Medal] in April 1981, the CBE 
[Commander of the British Empire] in April 1986 and was knighted 
(KCB) [Knight Commander of the Bath] in the 1994 New Year's 
Honours. 
  He is currently Chairman of the Army Parachute Association 
and Commodore of the Army Sailing Association. He is married and 
has two sons. 

</TEXT>

