<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Preview NATO Summit; View Expansion, Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Dehaene: NATO Should Study Air Raid Option </H4>
<F P=102> AU0901171594 Paris AFP in English 1651 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0901171594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Jan 9 (AFP) -- The NATO summit opening 
here Monday [10 January] should "seriously" study the 
possibility of launching air attacks against Bosnian Serbs, 
Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene said Sunday. 
  Speaking after talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton, 
Dehaene said the West had to send a signal of its determination 
to act in the face of continuing bloodshed in Bosnia. 
  NATO agreed in August to launch air raids on Serbs in the 
former Yugoslav republic if requested by the United Nations to 
break the siege of Sarajevo and other Moslem communities. 
  But it has yet to be given the green light by UN Secretary 
General Butrus Butrus-Ghali, even as the shelling of Sarajevo 
has intensified in recent days. 
  "We must seriously consider the possibility of launching air 
raids," Dehaene told reporters after his meeting with Clinton. 
"I think that more and more countries agree on this." 
  France is pressing the two-day summit to take strong action 
on Bosnia but there is little sign the United States is ready to 
support any new initiative. 
  Washington once strongly supported air raids, but U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher last week repeated 
warnings that such attacks were bound to endanger UN forces 
guarding relief operations on the ground. 

</TEXT>

