<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Preview NATO Summit; View Expansion, Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Major Invites East To `Move Closer' </H4>
<F P=102> AU1001095894 Paris AFP in English 0951 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001095894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Jan 10 (AFP) -- NATO will issue a "wide 
invitation" during a two-day summit here for the countries of 
the former Soviet bloc to move closer to the Atlantic alliance, 
British Prime Minister John Major said Monday [10 January]. 
  "It will be a very wide invitation that is extended to 
Central and East European nations, Russia, Ukraine, and I very 
much hope they will take it up," Major told reporters on his 
arrival at NATO headquarters. 
  He said the Partnership for Peace plan under which the North 
Atlantic Treaty Organization would give former East bloc 
countries a cooperative link with the Atlanic alliance but not 
full membership was the best option at present. 
  The British leader also said the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina 
was of concern to NATO heads of state and government, 
"particularly amongst those with large numbers of troops there." 
  But he indicated there was unlikely to be any major change 
in 
NATO policy on the 21-month conflict, noting that the alliance 
had already approved the use of air strikes if requested by the 
United Nations. 
  "That was the position and that remains the position today," 
Major said. 

</TEXT>

