<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Preview NATO Summit; View Expansion, Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   France To Insist on Bosnia Plan </H4>
<F P=102> BR0701150294 Brussels LA LIBRE BELGIQUE in French 7 Jan 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> BR0701150294 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels LA LIBRE BELGIQUE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia `Invited' To Join NATO </F>
Summit"] 
  [Text] Bosnia, where the situation of local population and 
blue helmets is increasingly deteriorating (UN Protection Force 
[UNPROFOR] military observers said that numerous civilians are 
about to die of starvation in the region of Kakanj), will be the 
last-minute "guest" of the upcoming NATO summit to be held on 
10-11 January in Brussels. Besides, France called upon NATO to 
send the warring factions a clear political message to stop 
hostilities. 
  The issue of the former Yugoslavia will not be on the agenda 
of the 16 NATO heads of state and government but will 
nevertheless be raised by France, which hopes that NATO, and 
also the United States, will strongly support the peace efforts 
deployed, so far in vain, by the Europeans, indicated officials 
wanting to preserve anonymity. Paris would like NATO to support 
the peace plan elaborated by the Twelve in December. 
  The same officials say that the other topics on the summit 
agenda, namely the U.S. Partnership for Peace proposal offered 
to the ex-Soviet Bloc and the reinforcement of the European 
defense strength, should be endorsed without difficulty by the 
heads of state and government. 
  On the other hand, the discussion on Bosnia might be more 
lively owing to persistent divergences of opinion among the 
Allies. Furthermore, reliable sources say that Washington does 
not want the Bosnian issue to overshadow its proposal to open up 
NATO to East European countries, which in its opinion, remains 
the priority issue of the summit. 

</TEXT>

