<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Calls `Partnership for Peace' `Reasonable' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001130094 Paris AFP in English 1250 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001130094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Brussels, Jan 10 (AFP) -- NATO must expand 
gradually into East Europe with attention to the "special" 
importance of Russia and without undermining democratic reform 
there, British Prime Minister John Major said here Monday [10 
January]. [passage omitted] 
  French President Francois Mitterrand also cited the need to 
avoid "countering" the development of democracy in Russia. 
  He described the plan for gradual expansion endorsed by NATO 
leaders, known as Partnership for Peace, as "reasonable" and 
said it was "a form of real guarantee" for the security needs of 
the new democracies in East Europe. 
  A spokesman for Mitterrand said former Soviet states now 
worried about the potential of renewed Russian expansionism 
should interpret the partnership as a promise that "now war 
could threaten their territorial integrity and sovereignty." 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

