<H3> <TI>   Vranitzky, Busek Announce New National Service Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701183494 Salzburg SALZBURGER NACHRICHTEN in German 7 Jan 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU0701183494 </F>
<F P=104>  Salzburg SALZBURGER NACHRICHTEN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Still a Chance for National </F>
Alternative Service Reform"] 
  [Text] Vienna -- On the holiday [Epiphany, 6 January], 
Franz Vranitzky and Erhard Busek, the chairmen of the coalition 
parties, announced new initiatives to bring the talks on 
alternative national service to a conclusion after all. As has 
been reported, [Defense Minister] Werner Fasslabend, Austrian 
People's Party [OeVP], and [Interior Minister] Franz Loeschnak, 
Social Democratic Party of Austria [SPOe], suspended the talks 
on Tuesday without any results. The contentious issue was the 
duration of national alternative service. 
  SPOe Chairman Vranitzky said the SPOe has already 
contributed 
so much in terms of improvements and concessions that he does 
not understand why the OeVP cannot "take this last step." He 
wants to call on Loeschnak to talk with Fasslabend once again, 
the chancellor said. 
  Busek said he would be pleased if Vranitzky gave Loeschnak 
new leeway for negotiations. 

</TEXT>

