<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   CDU Calls Yeltsin, Kozyrev `Potentially Imperialistic' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701153094 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU in German 
7 Jan 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU0701153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "wtr": "Bonn Also Going To Be Opponent"] </F>
  [Text] Bonn, 6 Jan -- The Christian Democratic Union [CDU] 
has reacted with massive attacks to Moscow's demand not to 
extend NATO to the East. What President Boris Yeltsin and 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev have said is "potentially 
imperialistic," said CDU foreign policy spokesman Karl Lamers on 
6 January. He called upon the West, and above all Germany, "to 
show" Russia that one could not only be a partner, but "also an 
opponent." 
  Lamers accused Yeltsin and Kozyrev of exerting political and 
economic pressure on Russia's neighbor states and of using its 
armed forces for "intimidation" in some cases, such as the 
Baltics and the Caucasus. Moscow was only interested in 
"ensuring maximum influence," said Lamers. To prevent the West 
from extending NATO to the Russian border, the Russian 
leadership was using "the West's concerns" about a new Russian 
imperialism "as an instrument," said Lamers a few days prior to 
the NATO summit in Brussels on 10 January, which will discuss a 
possible opening up of the alliance to the East. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

