<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bomb Attack on NATO Offices: No Injuries Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001081594 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 0745 
GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001081594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] There was a bomb attack in Rome last night against a 
six-story building where several NATO offices and a bank are 
located. The explosion took place on the eve of the NATO summit 
in Brussels, which U.S. President Bill Clinton is attending. 
The two-kilo explosive device went off shortly after 0100 in 
the Eur district on the outskirts of Rome. No one was hurt, but 
material damage was significant. 
  According to an eyewitness, four people left the scene in an 
Alfa 33 immediately after the blast in Viale Beethoven, near 
Piazza Don Sturzo, where the former headquarters of the 
Christian Democratic Party were located. The explosion caused a 
one-meter-wide crater. Bomb disposal experts immediately went to 
the scene to find out what sort of explosive was used by the 
terrorists. Investigators must also establish whether last 
night's bomb attack against the NATO offices in Rome is 
connected with the start of the summit in Brussels. 

</TEXT>

