<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bomb Explodes at NATO Offices in Rome </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1001081894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 0625 GMT 10 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1001081894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bomb at NATO Offices in Rome"] </F>
  [Text] Rome, 10 Jan (ANSA) -- A two-kilogram bomb exploded 
outside the NATO Command Defense College offices in Rome shortly 
after midnight on Sunday night [9 January], causing some damage 
but no injuries, police reported. 
  No one has yet claimed responsibility for the bomb, which 
was 
placed next to one of the marble columns supporting the 
two-storey building and left a crater about 1.5 meters deep. 
  Security at all NATO offices in Europe was immediately 
tightened in response to the bombing, Italian officials said. A 
NATO summit begins Monday morning in Brussels. 
  The NATO Defense College is in the EUR neighborhood, on the 
southern outskirts of the capital, in the same building as a 
branch of Banca Nazionale dell'Agricoltura [National 
Agricultural Bank] and some municipal offices. The building has 
a closed-circuit camera security system and 24-hour guard 
service but no one reportedly noticed anything suspicious before 
the explosion. 
  Eyewitnesses reported seeing four men leaving the site of 
the 
attack aboard a gray Alfa Romeo shortly before the bombing. 

</TEXT>

