<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Alternate Foreign Minister, U.S. Ambassador Meet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0701133694 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0701133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Greek Alternate Foreign Minister Theodhoros Pangalos 
met this morning with U.S. Ambassador Thomas Niles. Pangalos 
briefed Niles on the positions of the Greek presidency of the 
European Union [EU]. During the meeting, Pangalos and Niles 
also discussed the upcoming meeting between U.S. President Bill 
Clinton, Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, and EU Commission 
President Jacques Delors. In a statement after the meeting, the 
U.S. ambassador stressed that there is complete agreement on the 
issues Greece is planning to promote during the six months in 
which it will exercise the EU presidency. Niles stressed that 
the Yugoslav dispute is one of the priority issues, and he 
expressed U.S. support for the ongoing UN efforts, through the 
mediation of Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg, for a peaceful 
settlement. He also expressed the opinion that there will be no 
disagreement between the United States and the EU on settling 
the problem in Bosnia-Herzegovina. He added, however, that we 
should also wait for the results of the tripartite meeting 
mediated by Stoltenberg and Lord Owen. 

</TEXT>

