<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Decision Rests With Security Council </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001193094 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1800 
GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bosnia was one of the main topics discussed at the 
National Assembly this afternoon. UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali was the guest of the Assembly's Foreign Affairs 
Commission and of the Commission chairman, Valery Giscard 
d'Estaing. Luc Lemonnier asked the UN secretary general who 
would give the go-ahead should NATO army officials ask for 
permission to use artillery or air strikes against Serbian guns 
in Bosnia. Butrus Butrus-Ghali's answer was as follows: 
  [Begin Butrus-Ghali recording] It is not for the generals to 
ask me for permission, it is for the secretary general's special 
representative, who is responsible for three distinct 
operations. The first is the military operation, the second is 
the humanitarian operation -- we look after 2 million refugees 
-- and the third corresponds to the negotiations which are 
currently under way in Geneva, or which may take place in Bonn 
over the next few days. Everything is contingent upon these 
three elements. 
  If the secretary general's special representative asks, I 
will be only too pleased to accept this request. The political 
power belongs to the Security Council, which gives a mandate. 
The Security Council may give a mandate to NATO, just as it may 
not give any mandate. The decision lies with the Security 
Council, i,e., the 15 members of the Security Council; i.e., the 
five permanent members who have a right of veto. They are the 
ones who will decide. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

