<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgium's Dehaene Stresses Political Solution in Yugoslavia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001230894 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 2130 
GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001230894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At the NATO summit in Brussels, U.S. President Bill 
Clinton asked his European partners to take military action in 
Bosnia against the Serbs if the situation in Sarajevo, the 
capital, does not improve. 
  As for President Mitterrand, he called on the Atlantic 
alliance to give concrete expression to pledges to Bosnia 
through actions, in particular UN resolutions on the protection 
of UN soldiers. 
  Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene said that, if a 
solution is to be found, it can only be a political one. He 
spoke to our correspondent in Brussels, Quentin Dickinson: 
  [Begin recording] [Dehaene] It is clear that a solution in 
Yugoslavia will either be a political one, or there will be no 
solution at all. There is no such thing as a purely military 
solution because if a durable solution is to be found, there 
must be an agreement between the various parties. 
  However, when no rule is being respected, when no agreement 
is being respected, I believe that it is necessary to step up 
pressure, probably by increasing sanctions and by using relevant 
means in order to have the UN resolutions enforced on the 
ground, possibly by demanding an air force, as was planned at 
some stage. In any case, if we demand the enforcement of the 
resolutions, it is also necessary to draw conclusions. 
  [Dickinson] Air strikes? 
  [Dehaene] I think it is a means we should be able to use. If 
we say that we want all UN resolutions to be enforced, it is one 
of the consequences. Or else it is better not to say that. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

