<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Major Announces `Limited' Ministerial Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101132494 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1303 GMT 11 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101132494 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Chris Moncrieff, PRESS ASSOCIATION political editor] </F>
  [Text] The Prime Minister today announced limited 
ministerial changes in the House of Lords following the 
resignation of the Earl of Caithness as Minister of State, 
Transport, after the death of his wife. 
  Mr Major has contained the changes so as to disturb as 
little 
as possible the ministerial structure in the Lords. 
  Lord Caithness's portfolio will be undertaken at the lower 
level of Under-Secretary, by Lord Mackay of Ardbrecknish, 
promoted from the Whips' Office. 
  Lord Mackay, 55, as Mr John Mackay, sat in the House of 
Commons from 1979 to 1987, first as MP [Member of Parliament] 
for Argyll and later for the redrawn constituency of Argyll and 
Bute. 
  The resignation also gives Mr Major an opportunity to 
promote 
Lord Strathclyde, 33, from Under-Secretary to Minister of State 
at the Department of Trade and Industry. 
  Lady Denton, 58, becomes Under-Secretary Northern Ireland, 
swapping jobs with the Earl of Arran, 55, who becomes 
Under-Secretary, Environment. Downing Street declined to give a 
reason for this exchange of posts. 
  A new whip, to replace Lord Mackay, will be announced later. 

</TEXT>

