<F P=100> IRELAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Army, Police Base Hit by Explosion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101024194 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 0103 GMT 11 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101024194 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By John Deane, PRESS ASSOCIATION] </F>
  [Text] A joint Army and police base in Northern Ireland was 
rocked by an explosion early today (Tuesday). 
  A number of people were injured in the blast at the base at 
Crossmaglen, South Armagh, at around 12.20 am. 
  No further details about the casualties were immediately 
available, the RUC [Royal Ulster Constabulary] said. 
  Yesterday evening a mortar bomb exploded at the base. 
  No-one was injured in that attack, but the area around the 
heavily-fortified post was sealed off while Army bomb experts 
carried out a search. The base was not evacuated. 
  Later an RUC spokesman said the blast came as military 
personnel were attempting to recover the vehicle used in the 
earlier mortar bomb attack. 
  The explosion happened inside the base. It is believed two 
soldiers were injured in the attack, but the extent of their 
injuries is not yet known. 

</TEXT>

