<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saudi Official Visits, To Meet With Ministers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001185094 Paris AFP in English 1836 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001185094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 10 (AFP) -- Saudi Arabia's Eastern 
Province governor Prince Muhammad Bin-Fahd arrived here on 
Monday [10 January] for a three-day official visit and meetings 
with French President Francois Mitterrand and Prime Minister 
Edouard Balladur scheduled for Wednesday [as received]. 
  The governor, a son of King Fahd, was to hold talks Tuesday 
with Industry and Foreign Trade Minister Gerard Longuet, Defence 
Minister Francois Leotard and Interior Minister Charles Pasqua. 
  Prince Mohammad, sometimes described as the king's 
"businessman" although he has no government portfolio, was also 
scheduled to dine with French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe and 
meet with French business leader Francois-Xavier Ortoli. 
  The governor's visit, arranged some time ago at the 
invitation of both Mitterrand and Balladur, follows the latter's 
weekend visit to Riyadh during which France hoped to clinch 
major arms deals. 
  Instead, Balladur's visit ended only with the establishment 
of a committee of experts charged with Franco-Saudi economic 
dossiers. 
  Saudi Arabia is currently faced with financial problems 
resulting from falling oil prices and a debt backlog from the 
Gulf war three years ago. 
  The governor, whose province produces most of Saudi Arabia's 
oil, was likely to continue discussions with French leaders 
raised by Balladur at the weekend, French Foreign Ministry 
sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-58255 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu007_i_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-007 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Decision Made on Balladur Visit to China </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101154694 Paris AFP in English 1358 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 11 (AFP) -- A French Foreign Ministry 
official Tuesday [11 Janaury] denied a decision had been taken 
on a visit by Prime Minister Edouard Balladur to China later 
this month. 
  Reliable sources in Beijing had earlier said Balladur, 
accompanied by Foreign Minister Alain Juppe and Industry 
Minister Gerard Longuet would visit China from January 27 to 30 
to mark the 30th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic 
relations between the two countries. 
  Catherine Colonna, deputy spokesperson at the Foreign 
Ministry, said: "No decision has yet been taken on an eventual 
visit." 
  The sources in Beijing said a close Balladur aide, Jacques 
Friedman, visited China at the end of December to prepare for 
the visit which would come a year after a cooling in relations 
brought about by French sales of fighter aircraft to Taiwan. 
  Speaking on January 4, Juppe had said Paris this year hoped 
to rekindle relations with China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

