<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sarkozy Sees No Alternative to Economic Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001155394 Paris AFP in English 1529 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001155394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 10 (AFP) -- There is no alternative for 
France to its current economic policy for containing social 
costs and unemployment, Budget Minister Nicolas Sarkozy said on 
Monday [10 January]. 
  He urged members of the centre-right parties behind the 
coalition government to support the policy. Reforms would be 
introduced at a speed compatible with the main concern of 
maintaining social harmony. 
  Expressing the conviction that "as things stand, no other 
policy is possible," he said: "The two absolute priorities of 
the government in 1994 are the balancing of the health insurance 
budget and control of the increase in unemployment by all the 
means available to us." 
  Sarkozy, who is spokesman for the government, was giving a 
New Year message to the press. 
  During January the government would announce "important 
decisions" concerning health insurance. 
  He noted that Prime Minister Edouard Balladur wanted the 
government to work hard for recovery without paying undue 
attention to the timetable for a presidential election next year. 

</TEXT>

