<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government `Satisfied' With NATO Summit Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1101124094 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1130 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1101124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The government is satisfied with the NATO summit's 
decision on expanding the Alliance. 
  Briefing correspondents today, government spokesman Ioannis 
Kasoulidhis said Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou very 
correctly noted that the decision to include former Warsaw Pact 
and CSCE countries in the plan for cooperation on peace gives 
Cyprus the right to cooperate with NATO if it wants. Asked 
whether the government intends to express such an interest, 
Kasoulidhis replied that Cyprus is happy to have the right, but 
added that it does not intend to use it now. 
  Kasoulidhis said Papandreou did not raise the Cyprus issue 
at 
the NATO summit because he was there representing the European 
Union, not the Greek Government. The spokesman added that 
Papandreou planned to raise the Cyprus ssue during a luncheon 
for the NATO leaders. 

</TEXT>

