<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Denies Cross-Border Operation Into Syria </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1001222694 Istanbul HURRIYET in Turkish 9 Jan 94 p 18 </F>
<F P=103> NC1001222694 </F>
<F P=104>  Istanbul HURRIYET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of Internal Affairs and the General 
Staff have not confirmed the reports that the Turkish Armed 
Forces have carried out a cross-border operation into Syria. 
Stressing that the question of cross-border operations is 
always on Turkey's agenda, Prime Minister Tansu Ciller has said: 
"However, the latest operation must not be regarded as one 
specially planned for Syria." 
  Meanwhile, Internal Affairs Minister Nahit Mentese has also 
denied the reports on a cross-border operation into Syria. 
Stressing that the security forces launched an operation the 
night before last in the Suruc District of Sanliurfa, which is 
on Turkey's border with Syria, Mentese said: "The operation in 
Suruc is continuing. Suruc and Syria may have been confused. 
Six terrorists have been killed or captured in the operation 
thus far." 
  Mentese also said an operation was carried out in Tunceli at 
about the same time. Five terrorists were killed or captured. 
  The officials affiliated with the General Staff have said 
the 
operation in Suruc may have been regarded as one aimed at Syria. 
Stressing that a cross-border operation into Syria has not taken 
place, the officials said the operation in Suruc is continuing. 

</TEXT>

