<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel `Understanding' of Polish NATO Stand </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001202894 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
10 Jan 93 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU1001202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "C.G.": "Kinkel Expresses Understanding for </F>
Poland"] 
  [Text] Bonn, 9 Jan -- Foreign Minister Kinkel has met 
Polish Foreign Minister Olechowski in Berlin to discuss Warsaw's 
wish to join NATO. Kinkel expressed understanding for Poland's 
calls for clear-cut prospects regarding NATO membership. Germany 
sees itself as an advocate acting on behalf of the reformist 
states of Central and East Europe. Kinkel said Poland's 
admission to the alliance could be the result of an 
"evolutionary process" first of all, but at the NATO conference, 
Germany would urge that an unmistakable sign be given "that the 
alliance is essentially open to new members." Chancellor Kohl 
has said NATO's offer of Partnership for Peace should not just 
amount to a diplomatic formula, but must contain "a clear-cut 
statement of future prospects for admission to NATO." It is 
also being said in Bonn that Kohl is counting on bringing the 
Central European states Poland, Hungary, and the Czech Republic 
into European Union structures. Even if they are not full EU 
members, Kohl is evidently thinking about involving those 
countries in European political cooperation with their status to 
be established at some later date. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

