<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentaries Discuss Brussels NATO Conference </TI></H3>
<H4>   Policy Becoming CIS `Right of Veto' </H4>
<F P=102> AU1101113694 Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG in German 11 Jan 94 
p 4 </F>

<F P=103> AU1101113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial by "jj": "Beautiful, Mysterious Formulas"] </F>
  [Text] The debate about NATO membership for the East 
European states is as honest as all diplomacy that faces an 
insoluble dilemma, meaning that it is nothing special. One half 
of the dilemma consists of the conviction that the former 
satellites of the Soviet Union need and deserve a safe home. 
The other half is that the West cannot offer them membership in 
the alliance. 
  There are good and not so good reasons for the denial. The 
latter include consideration for Moscow's irritability, which is 
ultimately turning into a Russian right of veto over Western 
policies. The better reasons include the fear of a watered-down 
alliance and of the acceptance of states that would bring too 
many internal and external conflicts into the alliance. In 
fact, NATO has always drawn its strength from a solid foundation 
of identical interests and institutions (with the exception of 
Greece and Turkey). 
  This dilemma explains the vague rhetoric, the "beautiful, 
mysterious formulas," as the Estonian president put it. They 
include neither dates nor obligations. Still, there is a better 
way to avoid the dilemma. Clinton outlined it when he appealed 
to the West to speak more about "trade than aid." "Trade 
barriers" must be removed quickly. There is no point in 
"applauding market reforms" while only "offering selective 
access to our markets." Markets mean growth, and prosperity 
legitimizes the democratic reform policy -- probably more than 
an abstract alliance membership. Moreover, this method has the 
advantage of really helping the East Europeans without offending 
the Russians. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

