<F P=100> PORTUGAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cavaco Welcomes Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001211694 Lisbon RTP Internacional Television in 
Portuguese 1900 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001211694 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RTP Internacional Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] NATO is to open its doors to East European 
countries but with caution in order not to upset Russia. The 
enlargement has been postponed but a new phase of cooperation 
starts, a sort of sweetener for the candidates. It is possible 
that in the future there will be NATO intervention without the 
Americans. Washington does not want to be involved in some of 
the complex situations such as Bosnia and leaves the decision to 
its European NATO friends. Antonio Esteves Martins reports from 
Brussels. 
  [Martins] By signing the American proposal, Partnership for 
Peace, today the 16 member states have definitively relaunched 
NATO into a new area of cooperation and have opened the door for 
new membership but only in the medium or even long term. This 
is the price to be paid in order not to irritate Russia's 
nationalists and to calm the Visegrad Four, the countries 
applying for immediate membership: Poland, Hungary, Czech 
Republic and Slovakia. 
  [Begin Cavaco recording in progress] ...a door which opens 
to 
a future enlargement. I think this will be an important 
contribution to a greater security in Europe without creating 
new divisions in Europe. The concern is not to create a new 
Iron Curtain, now situated a little further east. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

