<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Comments on Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101124194 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1000 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101124194 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto by by Kaija </F>
Kervinen in Kuopio; date not given -- recorded] 
  [Text] The Finnish Government will this week discuss NATO's 
Partnership for Peace offer. Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto 
was not yet able today to estimate when Finland will decide its 
stance to Partnership for Peace. 
  [Begin recording] [Haavisto] The Partnership for Peace idea 
is in itself a positive solution. It strengthens security in 
Europe, and in that sense it is in line with Finland's basic 
aims. In fact, Finland does not at present have a need for 
greater security and we do not need such a treaty in itself. 
However, it contains certain aspects, such as peacekeeping 
cooperation in which Finland would be a considerable 
contributing partner for the rest of Europe. The government 
will adopt a stance on this in due course. We will hear a more 
detailed report this afternoon on what timetable to follow when 
the decision is made on this matter, and this week the 
government's foreign affairs committee will discuss this 
situation for the first time. I cannot say when Finland's final 
decision will come. It requires very thorough familiarization 
and deliberation. 
  Regarding Vaeyrynen's stance, he is no doubt right in that 
we 
do not need such a treaty, but the government will nevertheless 
have to consider the matter as a whole from all aspects. 
  [Kervinen] Vaeyrynen is taking quite a critical view, 
perhaps 
because of these drawbacks. He says that there might be 
drawbacks from it for our neutrality. 
  [Haavisto] It is my view that this does not affect the 
neutrality one way or the other. This does not mean entering 
any military alliance, but this is only a treaty on cooperation 
in various matters and as it has been offered to all CSCE 
countries, including Russia, I feel that this does not yet have 
anything to do with neutrality, nor would this treaty endanger 
Finland's neutrality. It is then a different matter whether the 
treaty in general is a sensible thing for us, because we have 
invested more in the possibility that as member of the European 
Union, we would develop European security structures. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

