<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministers Agree to 11 Months Alternative Service </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1201115094 Vienna DIE PRESSE in German 12 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DIE PRESSE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "d.n.": "Eleven Months of Alternative Service </F>
With Immediate Effect"] 
  [Text] Vienna -- A breakthrough has been achieved finally 
in the lengthy negotiations on alternative national service: 
Effective 1 January 1994, the duration of alternative national 
service will be 11 months. 
  "I think it was a victory for our country's security," 
Defense Minister Werner Fasslabend (Austrian People's Party) 
told DIE PRESSE on Tuesday evening [11 January]. Effective 1 
January 1994, the duration of alternative national service will 
be 11 months. A further extension to 12 months could come into 
force beginning 1 January 1995, if the number of applications 
for alternative service between 1 May and 31 October 1994 
exceeds 3,000. 
  The new regulation will remain in force until the end of 
1995. Unless a further regulation is agreed before the end of 
1995, both the board examining reasons of conscience and the 
eight-month period of alternative service will be reintroduced. 
This is the compromise agreed upon yesterday by Fasslabend and 
Interior Minister Franz Loeschnak (Social Democratic Party of 
Austria), after consultations with their respective party 
chairmen. Fasslabend said: "Our patience did pay off. I think 
it is important that the government has found a solution." 
Interior Minister Loeschnak said that he did not expect an 
extension to 12 months. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-58315 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu008_a_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-008 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

